The Ex-MEP for the North West, Steven Woolfe, is the perfect guest for this week’s Shooting from the Lip with Jon Gaunt in a week which has been dominated by the Andy Burnham and Boris Johnson funding row.
There are still negotiations underway on an economic stimulus bill for pandemic relief in the US, even though it won't come before the November 3 election.

Today Lee Stranahan discussed current events, including the announcement that the DNI and FBI accused Iran & Russia of election interference in the 2020 election, NPR's statement on not covering Hunter Biden, Ghislaine Maxwell’s testimony being released, and how Biden’s laptop was subpoenaed for money laundering evidence.
On this episode of Fault Lines, hosts Jamarl Thomas and Shane Stranahan discuss the new economy the pandemic has created. The idea of Universal Basic Income is looking like a viable solution.

On 21 October, Secretary of State Mike Pompeo announced that Washington had designated the operations of six more Chinese media outlets as foreign missions. American observers have discussed Pompeo's move, asking whether the US may boast of a diversity of views and freedom of the press amid recent instances of censorship by corporate media.

In a sharp rebuff to China, which may complicate the ongoing border stand-off, India's Ministry of Defence announced on Monday that Australia would participate in the Malabar 2020 multilateral naval exercise. The announcement evinced massive interest among security observers, as after 13 years, the Malabar drills will feature the full Quad.
The US, UAE, and Israel have agreed to set up a fund worth over $3 billion to invest in projects in the Middle East.
Voter turnout at US presidential elections was as high as 81 percent at one point in the 19th century. But in the modern era the highest it ever reached was 62.8 percent in 1960.

On 21 October, the US Federal Bureau of Investigation pointed the finger of blame at Moscow and Tehran for alleged meddling in the US election campaign by manipulating "some US voter registration information". International observers have discussed Washington's obsession with Russian "interference".

The British House of Commons is debating a law that will make it much more difficult for war crimes to be prosecuted as well as for UK military forces to sue the Ministry of Defence, with the only exception currently being for "sexual misconduct".
